## `<file-level: imports>`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-rename-1 -->

### Purpose
Rename is the operation most filesystems get subtly wrong. Its own test file covers: same-parent, cross-parent, overwrite semantics, into-own-subtree, `RENAME_NOREPLACE`, `RENAME_EXCHANGE`, atomicity, and rename interaction with hard links + symlinks.

### Implementation Notes

```python
import pytest

from sqlite_fs.errors import (
    AlreadyExists,
    DirectoryNotEmpty,
    FilesystemError,
    NotFound,
    PermissionDenied,
)
```

---

## `test_rename_same_parent_file(as_root)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-rename-2 -->

### Postconditions

```python
fd = as_root.create("/a")
as_root.write(fd, b"data", offset=0)
as_root.close_fd(fd)

inode_before = as_root.stat("/a").inode
as_root.rename("/a", "/b")

assert as_root.exists("/a") is False
assert as_root.exists("/b")
assert as_root.stat("/b").inode == inode_before   # inode preserved
fd = as_root.open("/b", flags=0)
assert as_root.read(fd, size=4, offset=0) == b"data"
as_root.close_fd(fd)
```

---

## `test_rename_cross_parent_file(as_root)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-rename-3 -->

### Postconditions

```python
as_root.mkdir("/dir1")
as_root.mkdir("/dir2")
fd = as_root.create("/dir1/a")
as_root.close_fd(fd)

inode_before = as_root.stat("/dir1/a").inode
as_root.rename("/dir1/a", "/dir2/a")

assert as_root.exists("/dir1/a") is False
assert as_root.stat("/dir2/a").inode == inode_before
```

